<subSubSection id="C32BA3A0FFAE780EFF50CC595566C542" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8EF02BFFAE780EFF50CC595566C542" blockId="4.[118,768,1359,1863]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
During the study of seed morphology of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFDAECC5956D5C762" box="[610,721,1359,1383]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFDAECC5956D5C762" box="[610,721,1359,1383]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and related species (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFEEECC79562CC782" author="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO" box="[290,552,1391,1415]" firstAuthor="FAGUNDEZ" journalOrPublisher="Pl. Biosyst." pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="328 - 336" part="143" refId="ref4236" refString="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO (2009). Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications. Pl. Biosyst. 143: 328 - 336." title="Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications" type="journal article" year="2009">FAGÚNDEZ &amp; IZCO, 2009</bibRefCitation>
) one of the samples collected from an 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFEE0CC995595C7A2" box="[300,401,1423,1447]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFEE0CC995595C7A2" box="[300,401,1423,1447]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
population clearly differed from the rest of the population with respect to the shape of the seeds and secondary sculpture. The seed morphology and details of the secondary ornamentation of this sample and a regular population of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFF0CCF19552CC422" box="[192,296,1551,1575]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFF0CCF19552CC422" box="[192,296,1551,1575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFE95CF1955C4C422" box="[345,448,1551,1575]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFE95CF1955C4C422" box="[345,448,1551,1575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are shown in 
<figureCitation id="130AECAEFFAE780EFD9CCF195688C422" box="[592,652,1551,1575]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[103,126,1848,1868]" captionTargetBox="[103,1479,281,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-26@5.[252,1348,397,1635]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 2. – Seeds of different species of Erica L. A: Erica tetralix L.; B: E. tetralix (detail of surface cells); C: E. tetralix × E. ciliaris; D: E. tetralix × E. ciliaris (detail of surface cells); E: E. ciliaris L.; F: E. ciliaris (detail of surface cells). [A: Fagúndez s.n., SANT-BG [119]; B: Fagúndez s.n., SANT-BG [211]; C-D: Fagúndez 3266, SANT; E: Fagúndez &amp; Reyes s.n., SANT-BG [266]; F: Fagúndez &amp; Reyes s.n., SANT-BG [273]]" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5762393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5762393/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
. The seeds of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFF5ECF3954FDC442" box="[146,249,1583,1607]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFF5ECF3954FDC442" box="[146,249,1583,1607]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are ovoid or ellipsoid, of ca. 
<quantity id="4CC95DCEFFAE780EFDEBCF395673C442" box="[551,631,1583,1607]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
, with a reticulate primary ornamentation and a smooth to vermiculate secondary sculpture of outer periclinal walls (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFDF5CF7954AFC4A2" author="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO" firstAuthor="FAGUNDEZ" journalOrPublisher="Pl. Biosyst." pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="328 - 336" part="143" refId="ref4236" refString="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO (2009). Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications. Pl. Biosyst. 143: 328 - 336." title="Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications" type="journal article" year="2009">FAGÚNDEZ &amp; IZCO, 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The seeds of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFE83CF9955B3C4A2" box="[335,439,1679,1703]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFE83CF9955B3C4A2" box="[335,439,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in size, but with an oblong-ellipsoid shape, a very faintly reticulate pattern and an indented secondary ornamentation (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFE3CCFD956F5C4E2" author="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO" box="[496,753,1743,1767]" firstAuthor="FAGUNDEZ" journalOrPublisher="Pl. Biosyst." pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="328 - 336" part="143" refId="ref4236" refString="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO (2009). Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications. Pl. Biosyst. 143: 328 - 336." title="Seed morphology of Erica L. sect. Loxomeria Salisb. ex Benth., sect. Eremocallis Salisb. ex Benth. and sect. Brachycallis I. Hansen, and its systematic implications" type="journal article" year="2009">FAGÚNDEZ &amp; IZCO, 2009</bibRefCitation>
). In this intermediate population, seeds are largely ellipsoid or ovoid, with a slightly reticulate pattern and an indented secondary ornamentation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32BA3A0FFAE780EFCBDC80F50BFC014" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B8EF02BFFAE780EFCBDC80F50BFC014" blockId="4.[843,1494,281,952]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
The parent plants were studied and the population was visited at the same locality in flowering time (Cercedo, 
<date id="FF8FD6EBFFAE780EFAA6C82F51CBC354" box="[1386,1487,313,337]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" value="2007-07">July 2007</date>
, see specimens studied). This population is part of a humid heathland with 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC3FC86F5041C394" authority="L." box="[1011,1093,377,401]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Ulex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC3FC86F5022C394" box="[1011,1062,377,401]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Ulex</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
where 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFB58C86F5120C394" box="[1172,1316,377,401]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFB58C86F5120C394" box="[1172,1316,377,401]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Erica ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is abundant and 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC87C88F57B8C3B4" box="[843,956,409,433]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC87C88F57B8C3B4" box="[843,956,409,433]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs whenever soils are moist. The plants are 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC87C8AF57B0C3D4" box="[843,948,441,465]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC87C8AF57B0C3D4" box="[843,948,441,465]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with no intermediate characters. Thus, we conclude that these seeds are product of the pollination of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFAABC8CF51D1C3F4" box="[1383,1493,473,497]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFAABC8CF51D1C3F4" box="[1383,1493,473,497]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plants with pollen from 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFB87C8EF50B0C014" box="[1099,1204,505,529]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFB87C8EF50B0C014" box="[1099,1204,505,529]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32BA3A0FFAE780EFCBDCB365144C1BD" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8EF02BFFAE780EFCBDCB365144C1BD" blockId="4.[843,1494,281,952]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFCBDCB365019C03D" box="[881,1053,544,568]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="watsonii">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFCBDCB3657AFC03D" box="[881,939,544,568]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Erica</emphasis>
× 
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC08CB365096C03D" box="[964,1170,544,568]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
watsonii (
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFBE7CB365096C03D" box="[1067,1170,544,568]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">E. ciliaris</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
× 
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFB7DCB365126C03D" box="[1201,1314,544,568]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFB7DCB36511DC03D" box="[1201,1305,544,568]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">E. tetralix</taxonomicName>
)
</emphasis>
is the most common of the European hybrids, described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFAD3CB565779C07D" author="BENTHAM" firstAuthor="BENTHAM" page="665" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="613 - 694" refId="ref4133" refString="BENTHAM, G. (1839). Erica L. In: CANDOLLE, A. DE (ed.), Prodr. 7: 613 - 694. Paris." type="journal article" year="1839">BENTHAM (1839: 665)</bibRefCitation>
from plants found by H. Watson and well known in the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFC24CB965143C09D" author="HOOKER, W. J. &amp; G. W. ARNOTT" box="[1000,1351,640,664]" firstAuthor="HOOKER" journalOrPublisher="London" page="255" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="255 - 257" part="6" refId="ref4357" refString="HOOKER, W. J. &amp; G. W. ARNOTT (1850). Erica L. British Fl. ed. 6: 255 - 257. London." title="Erica L" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="British Fl" year="1850">HOOKER &amp; ARNOTT, 1850: 255</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F326B0BBFFAE780EFA45CB9651D2C09D" box="[1417,1494,640,664]" name="France" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">France</collectingCountry>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFCABCBB357F3C0BD" author="NEYRAUT, M." box="[871,1015,672,696]" journalOrPublisher="Bull. Soc. Bot. France" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="326 - 329" part="47" refId="ref4524" refString="NEYRAUT, M. (1900). Nouvelle localite francaise de l'Erica watsoni et de quelques formes ou varietes de l'Erica tetralix et de l'Erica ciliaris. Bull. Soc. Bot. France 47: 326 - 329." title="Nouvelle localite francaise de l'Erica watsoni et de quelques formes ou varietes de l'Erica tetralix et de l'Erica ciliaris" type="journal article" year="1900">EYRAUT, 1900</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFBCBCBB650BFC0BD" author="ROUY" box="[1031,1211,672,696]" firstAuthor="ROUY" page="109" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="106 - 113" refId="ref4780" refString="ROUY, G. (1908). Erica L. Fl. France 10: 106 - 113." type="journal article" year="1908">ROUY, 1908: 109</bibRefCitation>
). There are also references from the Iberian Peninsula (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFBB2CBD651C8C0DD" author="PEREIRA- COUTINHO" box="[1150,1484,704,728]" firstAuthor="PEREIRA- COUTINHO" page="550" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="550 - 552" refId="ref4631" refString="PEREIRA- COUTINHO, A. X. (1939). Erica L. Fl. Portugal ed. 2: 550 - 552. Lisboa." type="journal article" year="1939">PEREIRA- COUTINHO, 1939: 550</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFC87CBF6500AC0FD" author="BAYER" box="[843,1038,736,760]" firstAuthor="BAYER" page="506" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" refId="ref4070" refString="BAYER, E. (1993). Erica L. In: CASTROVIEJO, S. &amp; al. (ed.), Fl. Iber." type="book" year="1993">BAYER, 1993: 506</bibRefCitation>
) although we have not found any material or precise localities. In the British populations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFAA8CA1651CBC11D" box="[1380,1487,768,792]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFAA8CA1651CBC11D" box="[1380,1487,768,792]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, where 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC57CA365035C13D" box="[923,1073,800,824]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="watsonii">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC57CA3657B7C13D" box="[923,947,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E.</emphasis>
× 
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC1DCA365035C13D" box="[977,1073,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">watsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is common, a very low percentage of seedlings have intermediate values for 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFAFDCA5651A0C15D" box="[1329,1444,832,856]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFAFDCA5651A0C15D" box="[1329,1444,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC87CA7657BEC17D" box="[843,954,864,888]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tetralix">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC87CA7657BEC17D" box="[843,954,864,888]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. tetralix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and may produce hybrid plants (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFAE5CA7651A3C17D" author="ROSE" box="[1321,1447,864,888]" firstAuthor="ROSE" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="201 - 210" refId="ref4738" refString="ROSE, R. J. (2007). The effects of hybridization on the small-scale variation in seed-bank composition of a rare plant species, Erica ciliaris L. Seed Sci. Res. 17: 201 - 210." type="journal article" year="2007">ROSE, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). In Spain no intermediates are commonly found although both species coexist in many localities (pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32BA3A0FFAE780EFCBDCADE5084C6A5" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8EF02BFFAE780EFCBDCADE5084C6A5" blockId="4.[843,1494,968,1184]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
The indented surface in the secondary sculpture of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFC87CAFE57B0C605" box="[843,948,1000,1024]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFC87CAFE57B0C605" box="[843,948,1000,1024]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seeds is uncommon for the European species of the genus. We have only recorded this feature in 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFAF7CD1E51A3C625" box="[1339,1447,1032,1056]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ciliaris">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFAF7CD1E51A3C625" box="[1339,1447,1032,1056]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. ciliaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some populations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C318BA8FFAE780EFBEFCD3E50BAC645" authority="Guss." authorityName="Guss." box="[1059,1214,1064,1088]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Erica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sicula">
<emphasis id="B9452C39FFAE780EFBEFCD3E5079C645" box="[1059,1149,1064,1088]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">E. sicula</emphasis>
Guss.
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA08DDAFFAE780EFB00CD3E51C2C645" author="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO" box="[1228,1478,1064,1088]" firstAuthor="FAGUNDEZ" journalOrPublisher="Turkish J. Bot." pageId="4" pageNumber="55" pagination="643 - 651" part="35" refId="ref4294" refString="FAGUNDEZ, J. &amp; J. IZCO (2011). Seed morphology and anatomy of the Mediterranean pentamerous species of Erica (Ericaceae). Turkish J. Bot. 35: 643 - 651." title="Seed morphology and anatomy of the Mediterranean pentamerous species of Erica (Ericaceae)" type="journal article" year="2011">FAGÚNDEZ &amp; IZCO, 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The outer periclinal walls of the testa cells are collapsed to the inner walls that present pits, allowing the cell surface to display this indented pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
